Albrecht,

The reason is simply that it is not particularly hard to numerically
solve u(T,v) = u_0 for T,  since (du/dT)_v = c_v is smooth and
monotonic.  Also, although this is probably not strictly necessary,
often this transformation from u to T is done in a way that is specific
to a particular equation of state (e.g. ideal gas).  The formulation in
terms of u works in principle for any equation of state.  That having
been said, however, it would probably not be hard at all to create a
modified Reactor class that was formulated in terms of T rather than u.
  Would this be useful to have?

By the way - I have just implemented sensitivity analysis for reactor
networks.  It is not released yet, but it should be later this week. It
will allow you to compute the sensitivity of any species (gas or
surface) in any reactor in the network, with respect to any reaction
(homogeneous or heterogeneous) in any other reactor in the network (or
the same one).

Dave


